From Zero to Expert!


---

1. What is JavaScript?

JavaScript is a high-level, dynamic programming language used to create interactive behavior on web pages. It's one of the core technologies of the web, alongside HTML and CSS.

Use Cases:

Dynamic webpage content

Form validation

Event handling

Asynchronous requests (AJAX)

Game development

Backend (Node.js)



---

2. Modern JavaScript (ES6+ Features)

JavaScript has evolved significantly. Key features include:

let and const for block-scoped variables

Arrow functions () => {}

Template literals: Hello ${name}

Destructuring: const {name, age} = person;

Spread & Rest operators: ...

Modules: import/export

Classes and inheritance



---

3. Variables and Data Types

let name = "John";        // String
const age = 30;           // Number
let isAdmin = true;       // Boolean
let user = null;          // Null
let x;                    // Undefined


---

4. Functions and Arrow Functions

function greet(name) {
  return Hello, ${name};
}

const greetArrow = (name) => Hello, ${name};


---

5. DOM Manipulation

The DOM (Document Object Model) allows JavaScript to interact with HTML elements.

const button = document.querySelector("button");
button.addEventListener("click", () => {
  alert("Button Clicked!");
});


---

6. Arrays and Objects

const fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];
const user = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 25,
  greet() {
    return Hi, I'm ${this.name};
  }
};


---

7. Asynchronous JavaScript

Callbacks

Promises

async/await


async function fetchData() {
  const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
  const data = await response.json();
  console.log(data);
}


---

8. JavaScript in 2025

Enhanced TypeScript compatibility

Edge runtime with Deno and Bun

Built-in module support in modern browsers

Native support for top-level await

ES2025 features: Records, Tuples (stage 3)
